com.oracle.truffle.tck

Class TruffleTCK

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.oracle.truffle.tck.TruffleTCK

  • public abstract class TruffleTCK
extends Object
    Test compatibility kit (the TCK) is a collection of tests to certify your language implementation compliance. If you want your language to be compliant with most recent requirements of the Truffle infrastructure and tooling, subclass, implement protected methods and include in your test suite: 
     public class MyLanguageTCKTest extends TruffleTCK {
   @Override
   protected PolyglotEngine prepareVM() {
     // create the engine
     // execute necessary scripts
   }

   @Override
   protected String fourtyTwo() {
     return // name of function that returns 42
   }

   // and so on...
 }
    The TCK is carefully designed to accommodate differences between languages. The TCK doesn't dictate what object your language is using to represent numbers or strings internally. The TCK doesn't prescribe the precise type of values returned from your language evaluations. The tests just assume that if the result is supposed to be a number, the returned value will be an instance of Number or be convertible to a Number and keeps sufficient level of precision. Similarly for strings. As such the tests in the TCK should be applicable to wide range of languages. Should there be a test that cannot be implemented in your language, it can be suppressed by overriding its test method and doing nothing: 
       @Override
   public void testFortyTwo() {
     // do nothing
   }

    The primary goal of the TCK is to ensure your language implementation plays well with other languages in the PolyglotEngine - e.g. that data can be exchanged between your and other languages. The interop package defines what types of data can be interchanged between the languages and the TCK does its best to make sure all these data are really accepted as an input on a boundary of your language implementation. That doesn't mean such data need to be used internally, many languages do conversions in their foreign access nodes to more suitable internal representation. Such conversion is fully acceptable as nobody prescribes what is the actual type of output after executing a function/code snippet in your language.

    Should the TCK be found unsuitable for your language implementation please speak-up (at Truffle/Graal mailing list for example) and we do our best to analyze your case and adjust the TCK to suite everyone's needs.

    0.8 or earlier

      • prepareVM

        protected PolyglotEngine prepareVM()
                            throws Exception
        This methods is called before each test is executed. It's purpose is to set a PolyglotEngine with your language up, so it is ready for testing. Execute any scripts you need, and prepare global symbols with proper names. The symbols will then be looked up by the infrastructure (using the names provided by you from methods like TruffleTCK.plusInt()) and used for internal testing.
        Returns:
        initialized Truffle virtual machine
        Throws:
        Exception - thrown when the VM preparation fails
        Since:
        0.8 or earlier

      • prepareVM

        protected PolyglotEngine prepareVM(PolyglotEngine.Builder preparedBuilder)
                            throws Exception
        Configure your language inside of provided builder. The method should do the same operations like TruffleTCK.prepareVM(), but rather than doing them from scratch, it is supposed to do the changes in provided builder. The builder may be pre-configured by the TCK - for example PolyglotEngine.Builder.executor(java.util.concurrent.Executor) may be provided or global symbols specified, etc.
        Parameters:
        preparedBuilder - the builder to use to construct the engine
        Returns:
        initialized Truffle virtual machine
        Throws:
        Exception - thrown when the VM preparation fails
        Since:
        0.12

      • returnsNull

        protected abstract String returnsNull()
        Name of a function that returns null. Truffle languages are encouraged to have their own type representing null, but when such value is returned from PolyglotEngine.eval(com.oracle.truffle.api.source.Source), it needs to be converted to real Java null by sending a foreign access isNull message. There is a test to verify it is really true.
        Returns:
        name of globally exported symbol
        Since:
        0.8 or earlier

      • plus

        protected String plus(Class<?> type1,
                      Class<?> type2)
        Name of function to add two numbers together. The symbol will be invoked with two parameters of type1 and type2 and expects result of type Number which's Number.intValue() is equivalent of param1 + param2. As some languages may have different operations for different types of numbers, the actual types are passed to the method and the implementation can decide to return different symbol based on the parameters.
        Parameters:
        type1 - one of byte, short, int, long, float, double class
        type2 - one of byte, short, int, long, float, double class
        Returns:
        name of globally exported symbol
        Since:
        0.8 or earlier

      • countInvocations

        protected abstract String countInvocations()
        Name of a function that counts number of its invocations in current PolyglotEngine context. Your function should somehow keep a counter to remember number of its invocations and always increment it. The first invocation should return 1, the second 2 and so on. The returned values are expected to be instances of Number.

        The function will be used to test that two instances of your language can co-exist next to each other. Without being mutually influenced.

      • compoundObject

        protected String compoundObject()
        Name of a function that returns a compound object with members representing certain operations. In the JavaScript the object should look like: 
         var obj = {
   'fourtyTwo': function TruffleTCK.fourtyTwo(),
   'plus': function TruffleTCK.plusInt(),
   'returnsNull': function TruffleTCK.returnsNull(),
   'returnsThis': function() { return obj; }
 };
 return obj;
        The returned object shall have three functions that will be obtained and used exactly as described in their Javadoc - e.g. TruffleTCK.fourtyTwo(), TruffleTCK.plusInt() and TruffleTCK.returnsNull(). In addition to that there should be one more function returnsThis that will return the object itself again.
        Returns:
        name of a function that returns such compound object
        Since:
        0.8 or earlier

      • valuesObject

        protected String valuesObject()
        Name of a function that returns a compound object with members representing certain primitive types. In the JavaScript the object should look like: 
         var obj = {
   'byteValue': 0,
   'shortValue': 0,
   'intValue': 0,
   'longValue': 0,
   'floatValue': 0.0,
   'doubleValue': 0.0,
   'charValue': '0',
   'stringValue': '',
   'booleanVlaue': false
 };
 return obj;
        The returned object shall have slots for these values that can be read and written to. Various test methods try to read and modify the values. Each invocation of the function should yield new object.
        Returns:
        name of a function that returns such values object
        Since:
        0.8 or earlier

      • countUpWhile

        protected String countUpWhile()
        Create a while-loop execution in your language. Create a function that takes one parameter - another function and then repeatly counts from zero to infinity calling the provided function with a single argument - the value of the counter: 0, 1, 2, 3, etc. The execution is stopped while the value returned from the provided function isn't true. The code in JavaScript would look like: 
         function countUpWhile(fn) {
   var counter = 0;
   for (;;) {
     if (!fn(counter)) {
       break;
     }
     counter++;
   }
 }
        Returns:
        the name of the function that implements the while-loop execution
        Since:
        0.15

      • assertDouble

        protected void assertDouble(String msg,
                            double expectedValue,
                            double actualValue)
        Assert two double values are the same. Various languages may have different semantics with respect to double numbers. Some of the language may not support double or float values at all. Those languages may override this method and compare the values with as much precision as they like.

        Default implementation of this method calls Assert.assertEquals(java.lang.String, double, double, double) with delta 0.1.

        Parameters:
        msg - assertion message to display in case of error
        expectedValue - the value expected by the test
        actualValue - the real value produced by the language
        Throws:
        AssertionError - if the values are different according to the language semantics
        Since:
        0.8 or earlier

      • metaObjects

        protected String[] metaObjects()
        Provide at least one pair of functions that return a value and its meta-object converted to a String representation. The value's meta-object is found using TruffleLanguage.findMetaObject(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object), converted to a String by TruffleLanguage.toString(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object) and compared to the provided String representation. Provide names of an even number of functions, which return a value and value's meta-object converted to a String, respectively. The code in JavaScript could look like: 
         function numberValue() {
     return 42;
 }

 function numberType() {
     return "Number";
 }

 function functionValue() {
     return functionValue;
 }

 function functionType() {
     return "Function";
 }
        Returns:
        names of functions that return a value and value's meta-object, respectively.
        Since:
        0.22

      • valueWithSource

        protected String valueWithSource()
        Name of a function that returns a value for which a source location can be found using TruffleLanguage.findSourceLocation(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object). It needs to be possible to find the source location among currently loaded sources for verification. The code in JavaScript could look like (returns a function object, which should have a source associated): 
         function foo() {
 }

 function getValueWithASource() {
     return foo;
 }
        Returns:
        name of a function that returns a value with source location associated
        Since:
        0.22
